{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622879"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:06:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:06:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16828"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16828"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.23,0.23,0.09,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76652"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9519"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62149"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7180"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"},{"type":"tags","id":"8505"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22488"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76652"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vertebral canal contains several important vascular structures. One of these is a network of valveless veins that extends along the entire length of the spinal column and connects with intracranial venous sinuses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical location of the internal vertebral venous plexus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epidural space","Subarachnoid space","Subdural space","Periosteal surface of vertebrae","Central vertebral canal"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidural space\u003C/strong\u003E contains the internal vertebral venous plexus, which consists of a network of valveless veins running the length of the vertebral canal. This venous system is important for draining blood from the vertebrae and spinal cord, and forms anastomoses with the intracranial venous sinuses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubarachnoid space\u003C/strong\u003E contains cerebrospinal fluid and is located between the arachnoid and pia mater\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubdural space\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential space between the dura and arachnoid mater\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eperiosteal surface of vertebrae\u003C/strong\u003E contains the external vertebral venous plexus, not the internal plexus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral vertebral canal\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the space within the vertebral body itself which contains bone marrow\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe internal vertebral venous plexus is clinically significant as it provides an alternative route for blood flow and can serve as a pathway for the spread of infection or metastatic disease, particularly from pelvic or thoracic malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The internal vertebral venous plexus is located in the epidural space of the vertebral canal.","The internal vertebral venous plexus forms part of the valveless venous system that connects intracranial and vertebral veins.","This venous network provides an alternative route for blood flow and can serve as a pathway for metastatic spread."],"references":["Borg N, Cutsforth-Gregory J, Oushy S, Huynh T, Savastano LE, Cloft HJ, Lanzino G, Brinjikji W. Anatomy of Spinal Venous Drainage for the Neurointerventionalist: From Puncture Site to Intervertebral Foramen. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2022 Apr;43(4):517-525. doi: 10.3174/ajnr.A7409. Epub 2022 Jan 27. PMID: 35086801; PMCID: PMC8993202.","Stringer MD, Restieaux M, Fisher AL, Crosado B. The vertebral venous plexuses: the internal veins are muscular and external veins have valves. Clin Anat. 2012 Jul;25(5):609-18. doi: 10.1002/ca.21281. Epub 2011 Oct 4. PMID: 21976364.","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62149"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16828"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62149"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T20:16:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T20:18:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9519"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76652"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":